Highlife fusion band, The Cavemen have revealed that they grew up listening to the soulful singer, Asa. In an exclusive chat with The Nation, the musical brothers described the France-based Nigerian singer as an inspiration. “We’ve always been listening to Asa since we were young. She is a good inspiration to us and we hope that she continues getting more grace,” one of half of the group, Kingsley Okorie said. Speaking on the acceptance of folk music by generation Z, the band said it is beyond their expectations. “Definitely, it is beyond our expectations. We felt deep inside our hearts that the world needed our kind of music. It is music that we always wanted to hear even as an individual and music lovers.   ANCOP set for NEC elections     Filmmaker Rev. Peace joins the political race     Aforevo to reward screenwriters with N1m in Nollywood   He added: “We really focus on making the making and the feelings of the music. That was wants drove us to this point.” - Advertisement - On the highpoint of their career so far, who is a singer and guitarist stated that it is everything that has been happening to them as a band. “A lot of huddles have been cross but glory be to the God. We have two albums out, done some groundbreaking shows and we had our Nigeria tour for the first time last year. So, everything has been happening is the highpoint.” The Orlu, Imo State natives emerged winners of the Best Alternative Album category at the 14th Headies award. They also noted that the biggest price they ever paid as a musician is time.